    id: "cd6e7d67-5800-47fc-a036-1b88b6f80fe5",
    description: `Adab kis ka Kyun aur Kaisy (Etiquettes — Whose and How?) is a comprehensive Urdu-language guide to Islamic manners, social etiquette, and behavioral conduct that addresses the fundamental questions of why etiquette matters in Islam, whose teachings we should follow regarding manners, and how to implement these teachings in practical daily life. The book systematically covers the vast topic of Islamic Adab — a concept that encompasses far more than simple table manners or polite phrases, extending to include one's entire approach to life, relationships, worship, and personal conduct as prescribed by the Quran and the Sunnah of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). The book's title reflects its tripartite structure: defining what Adab is, establishing its sources and authorities, and providing detailed practical guidance for implementation.

The book begins with a thorough discussion of the concept of Adab in Islamic thought, drawing upon the Quranic injunction to adopt the manners of the Prophet ("Indeed, you are upon a great moral character" — Surah Al-Qalam 4), the Hadith literature on the Prophet being sent to "perfect good character," and the extensive writings of classical scholars including Imam al-Ghazali's Ihya Ulum al-Din and Ibn al-Qayyim's Madarij al-Salikin. The author establishes that Islamic etiquette is not merely cultural tradition but a religious obligation rooted in divine revelation, and that the Prophet's Sunnah provides the most complete and perfect model of human behavior. The book then addresses the question "Whose Adab?" — explaining that the ultimate authority on manners is Allah through the Quran, followed by the Prophet through Hadith, followed by the practice of the Sahabah, followed by the consensus of scholars.

The practical sections of the book cover virtually every domain of human interaction. Chapters address the etiquettes of worship — including entering the mosque, performing ablution, reciting the Quran, and making dua — alongside the etiquettes of daily life including eating, drinking, sleeping, dressing, greeting, visiting the sick, attending funerals, conducting business, and interacting with family members. Specific chapters are dedicated to the rights and etiquettes between parents and children, between husbands and wives, between teachers and students, between neighbors, and between rulers and citizens. The book also covers the etiquettes of speech — controlling the tongue, avoiding gossip and slander, speaking gently, choosing appropriate topics, and knowing when to remain silent. Each chapter provides the relevant Quranic verses and Hadith, followed by classical scholarly commentary and practical advice for contemporary situations. The writing style is engaging and accessible, using examples from everyday South Asian Muslim life to illustrate abstract principles. The book has become a popular reference for families, Islamic schools, and anyone seeking to improve their character and conduct according to Islamic teachings.`
