    id: "f0c3b85b-bfc5-4933-8538-12852bf53957",
    description: `Ahkam-e-Tijarat aor Lain Dain K Masail (Rulings on Trade and Interest-Based Loans) is a focused Urdu-language book that addresses two of the most financially significant topics in Islamic jurisprudence — the rules governing business transactions (Tijarat) and the prohibition of interest (Riba or Lain Dain). In an era where conventional banking, credit cards, and interest-based financing are ubiquitous, this book provides Muslims with clear, evidence-based guidance on what constitutes permissible (Halal) business activity and what falls under the category of forbidden (Haram) financial dealings. The book is structured as a practical reference guide, organizing the complex rulings of Islamic commercial law into accessible categories that correspond to real-world financial situations.

The section on Tijarat (trade and business) covers the fundamental principles that distinguish a Halal transaction from a Haram one in Islamic law. The book explains the concept of mutual consent (Ijab wa Qabul) as the basis of all valid transactions, the requirement of transparency regarding the goods being sold (including any defects), the prohibition of selling what one does not own, the rules regarding forward sales and options, and the various types of sales contracts recognized by Islamic jurisprudence. Specific chapters address common business scenarios: the Islamic ruling on online shopping, e-commerce transactions, and digital payments; the permissibility and conditions of installment sales; the rules governing partnership businesses (Mudarabah and Musharakah); the Islamic perspective on insurance; and the ethics of advertising and marketing in Islam. The book distinguishes between valid sales contracts and those that are void (Batil) or defective (Fasid) due to elements of uncertainty (Gharar), deception, or coercion.

The section on Lain Dain (interest-based lending) provides one of the most comprehensive Urdu treatments of the Riba prohibition available. The book establishes the Quranic and Hadith evidence for the absolute prohibition of Riba, explaining the different categories of interest recognized by classical scholars and how they manifest in modern financial products. Chapters cover the specific rulings on bank interest, credit card interest, mortgage interest, student loans, car loans, and payday loans. The book also addresses commonly confused financial products, explaining the difference between interest and permissible profit-sharing arrangements, and analyzing various "Islamic banking" products to determine their compliance with Sharia principles. A practical section provides guidance for Muslims who are already involved in interest-based transactions and want to transition to Halal alternatives, addressing questions about existing loans, mortgages, and savings accounts. The book draws upon the works of classical Hanafi, Shafi'i, Maliki, and Hanbali jurists, as well as contemporary scholars and Islamic finance experts. Appendices include sample Halal business contracts, a checklist for evaluating financial products, and a glossary of Islamic finance terminology.`
