    id: "747ae1da-7965-4e90-af30-4513505d29bb",
    description: `Ajeeb Bisharat (Qissa Syedna Yaqoob) — Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya 10/30 is the tenth installment in the beloved "Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya" (Stories of the Prophets) series, presenting the story of Prophet Yaqoob (Jacob, peace be upon him) in engaging Urdu narrative form. The title "Ajeeb Bisharat" translates to "Amazing Good News," referring to the remarkable events surrounding Prophet Yaqoob's life — particularly the loss and recovery of his beloved son Prophet Yusuf (Joseph), which is one of the most detailed and emotionally powerful narratives in the entire Quran. This volume is part of a planned 30-volume series that aims to present the stories of all the Prophets mentioned in the Quran for a general Urdu readership, with each volume dedicated to a single Prophet or a group of related Prophetic narratives.

This volume tells the complete story of Prophet Yaqoob beginning with his lineage from Prophet Ishaq (Isaac) and Prophet Ibrahim (Abraham), through his early life, his marriage to the daughters of his uncle, the birth of his twelve sons who would become the ancestors of the twelve tribes of Bani Israel, the special bond he shared with his son Yusuf, and the devastating series of events that began when his jealous brothers threw Yusuf into a well. The narrative captures the profound grief that Prophet Yaqoob endured for years of separation from his beloved son, his steadfast patience and trust in Allah despite his suffering, and his eventual reunion with Yusuf in Egypt — events that are described in Surah Yusuf, one of the most beautiful and complete narratives in the Quran. The book explores the themes of parental love, sibling rivalry, patience through adversity, the consequences of jealousy, the fulfillment of divine promises, and the ultimate wisdom behind Allah's trials.

The writing style of the Silsila Qasas ul Anbiya series is designed to make Quranic narratives accessible and engaging for all ages. The Urdu prose is literary yet approachable, using vivid descriptions and emotional storytelling techniques that bring the ancient narratives to life. Quranic verses related to the story are woven into the narrative text, and each major event is accompanied by the relevant Quranic reference for readers who wish to study the original source. The book includes commentary sections that explain the lessons and moral principles derived from each episode of the story, making it suitable for both personal reading and educational use in Islamic schools and madrasas. Historical and geographical context is provided to help readers visualize the settings of the narrative — ancient Canaan, the route to Egypt, and the palaces of the Aziz of Egypt. This volume, as part of the broader series, represents a significant contribution to Urdu Islamic literature, providing readers with faithful, engaging retellings of the Quran's Prophetic stories that instill faith, patience, and moral awareness.`
