    id: "8b853ee6-2a94-4130-ba3c-f7bfc68c7377",
    description: `Al Quran Al Kareem 8 (16 Lines) Local is a locally produced edition of the Holy Quran in the standard South Asian 16-line format, identified as "Part 8" in a multi-part set. This edition is printed in the 16-line pagination system that is one of the most widely used formats in Pakistan and Indian subcontinent mosques, madrasas, and homes, where each page contains exactly 16 lines of Quranic text in the classic Naskh script. The "Local" designation indicates that this is a domestically published edition using local printing facilities and paper stock, making it an affordable option for daily reading, educational use, and mass distribution while maintaining acceptable quality standards.

The 16-line format used in this edition has been the standard for Quran publication in South Asia for over a century, with its pagination system so well established that Quran teachers and Hafiz instructors across the region reference specific page numbers and line numbers that are consistent across all 16-line editions regardless of publisher. This consistency is essential for the Hifz (memorization) system used in South Asian madrasas, where students memorize not only the words but also the visual layout of each page. The clear Naskh typography used in this edition is designed for maximum readability, with proper letter spacing, consistent line height, and full vowelization (Tashkeel) including Fathah, Kasrah, Dammah, Tanween, Sukun, and Shaddah marks. The Arabic text is printed in black ink on white offset paper with sufficient opacity to prevent show-through from the reverse side.

This "Part 8" contains approximately the 8th Juz (Para) of the Quran, covering portions of Surah Al-An'am and continuing through subsequent Surahs. The individual part format is particularly useful in educational settings where students are assigned specific Juz to memorize or study, in mosque settings where different Juz are used for Taraweeh prayers during Ramadan, and for individual readers who prefer to carry a single Juz for daily recitation rather than the complete Mushaf. The binding is designed to be durable enough for regular use while remaining lightweight and portable. Standard South Asian Quranic notation is maintained throughout, including Hizb divisions (each Juz divided into four Hizb), Ruku section markers, Sajdah indicators for verses requiring prostration, and the opening Bismillah for each Surah (except Surah At-Tawbah). This locally produced edition serves the vital function of making the Word of Allah accessible and affordable to the widest possible readership.`
